ificial name from Yiddish <i>perl</i> ‘pearl’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Perl</i> ‘pearl’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ate","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of recent origin. Possibly from a Germanic element <i>ano</i> ‘ancestor’. It has been linked to the Latin name <i>Achatius</i> ‘agate’."],"variants":[{"name":"Åge","meanings":["Of recent origin. Possibly from a Germanic element <i>ano</i> ‘ancestor’. It has been linked to the Latin name <i>Achatius</i> ‘agate’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Ate Perye was born about 1355, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Peyre, was 32 and his mother, Lady William Peyre, was 26. He married Catherine Iansdatter in 1386, in Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1355–":"umbes 1355–Surnud","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1362–1422":"1362–1422","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1380–1467":"1380–1467","1382–Female":"1382–Surnud","1325–1364":"1325–1364","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","about 1382":"umbes 1382","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1325":"1325","1467":"1467","1422":"